It is a hybrid quantum–classical EEG waveform classification system.

It takes EEG waveform images as input.

It performs noise removal and artifact suppression on EEG data.

It converts EEG images into numerical tensors for learning.

It uses a classical neural network encoder to reduce input dimensionality.

It uses a quantum circuit (PennyLane) as a feature extractor.

The quantum layer uses qubits, rotation gates, and entanglement.

Quantum features are passed to a classical classifier head.

The model predicts letters from A to Z.

Predicted letters are combined to form a word.

Training and testing are controlled via command-line arguments.

The system supports CPU, GPU, and Apple MPS acceleration.

It saves the best trained model automatically.

It demonstrates quantum-enhanced learning for EEG signals.

It compares quantum feature learning with classical encoding.

The entire pipeline runs in a single reproducible Python file.




EEG waveform classification
→ done by hybrid quantum–classical neural network

EEG image loading
→ done by PIL (Python Imaging Library)

Conversion to numerical format
→ done by NumPy arrays and PyTorch tensors

Noise removal in EEG signals
→ done by OpenCV median filtering

Artifact suppression (muscle / high-frequency noise)
→ done by OpenCV Gaussian blur

Signal normalization and scaling
→ done by NumPy statistical normalization

Dimensionality reduction of EEG images
→ done by classical neural network encoder (PyTorch Linear layers)

Non-linear feature extraction
→ done by quantum circuit implemented using PennyLane

Quantum encoding of classical features
→ done by RX rotation gates on qubits

Feature entanglement and expressivity
→ done by CNOT gates in the quantum circuit

Quantum measurement of features
→ done by Pauli-Z expectation values

Post-quantum feature transformation
→ done by PyTorch Linear layer

Final letter classification (A–Z)
→ done by classical neural network head (PyTorch)

Training and weight optimization
→ done by Adam optimizer (PyTorch)

Loss computation for learning
→ done by Cross-Entropy Loss

Model validation and accuracy calculation
→ done by PyTorch evaluation logic

Best model saving
→ done by PyTorch model checkpointing

Testing on unseen EEG data
→ done by trained model in inference mode

Word formation from predicted letters
→ done by Python string concatenation

Hardware acceleration (CPU / GPU / Apple MPS)
→ done by PyTorch device selection

Command-line execution (train / test)
→ done by argparse